{
  format: 1
  name: sort-tiebreak-int-key-uses-value-order
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.5", "§B.1", "§7.3"]
  tags: ["ordering"]
  note: '''
    §B.5: "A view follows its declared $sort, then inherited or synthetic row
    identity, then occurrence identity." §B.1 int: ascending is "mathematical
    integer order". Attack: when the declared $sort key TIES for every row, the
    tiebreak falls to the row identity — the int $key `id`. A runtime that
    ordered identity by the canonical D.2 key TEXT (base-10 digits) instead of
    the key VALUE would compare "10" < "2" < "3" and misorder the rows; the
    value order is 2 < 3 < 10.

    Every row has grp = "x", so the declared key `grp` is equal for all three;
    the result must be key-value ascending: id 2, id 3, id 10. Asserted on the
    distinct text `tag` fields (two, three, ten) so the wire form is
    unambiguous, and this order is exactly the REVERSE of the D.2 text
    misreading (ten, two, three), so the case is load-bearing. The seed member
    name is the int key's canonical base-10 text (D.2).
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.tieint@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      items: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "int"
        grp: "text"
        tag: "text"
      }
      $public: {
        bygrp: { $view: ".items { tag, grp, $sort: [grp] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      items: {
        "2":  { grp: "x", tag: "two" }
        "10": { grp: "x", tag: "ten" }
        "3":  { grp: "x", tag: "three" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.bygrp", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { tag: "two",   grp: "x" }
        { tag: "three", grp: "x" }
        { tag: "ten",   grp: "x" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
